AT APPROXIMATELY 2030 HOURS, SATURDAY, DECEMBER 2, 2000, AT NORTH YARD IN DETROIT MICHIGAN A CONRAIL CAR INSPECTOR NOTED ODOR EMANATING FRO TANK CAR NATX 82772 CONTAINING METHYL MERCAPTAN.  APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1630 HOURS, DECEMBER 3, 2000, A REPRESENTATIVE FROM ATOFINA ARRIVED AT THE SITE, EXAMINED THE TANK CAR AND DETERMINED THERE WAS A LOOSE "B" END LIQUID VALVE OPERATING STEM PACKING GLAND NUT.  ATOFINA SECURED THE TANK CAR.  AT APPROXIMATELY 0830 HOURS, DECEMBER 4, 2000 THE TANK CAR WAS OKAYED FOR DESTINATION.

column168: THIS PACKAGE IS BEING HELD IN THE MEMPHIS SORT CENTER'S DANGEROUS GOODS CAGE WHERE IT WILL REMAIN UNTIL THE SHIPPER GIVES FEDEX PACKAGE DISPOSITION INFORMATION.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP PER FEDEX SPILL CLEANUP POLICY.

THE SHIPPER WAS LOADING PRODUCT INTO AN ISO CONTAINER.  THERE WAS AN APPARENT MALFUNCTION DURING THE LOADING  PROCESS AND THE SHIPPER'S EQUIPMENT FAILED TO SHUT OFF ONCE THE TANK WAS FULL TO CAPACITY.  AS A RESULT, THERE WAS A PRODUCT RELEASE FROM THE TOP OF THE TANK DUE TO OVERFILLING.  THE RELEASE PRODUCT (APPROX. 800-1000 GALLONS) WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE LOADING CONTAINMENT AREA.  DRY ABSORBENT WAS PLACED OVER THE RELEASED PRODUCT ON THE GROUND.  THE RELEASED PRODUCT WAS CLEANED-UP AND PLACED IN BARRELS BY THE CONSIGNEE, AND DISPOSED OF ACCORDING TO THEIR POLICIES.

THE PAIL WAS RECOUPED INTO A CHEMICAL LINED, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED OVERPACK.  THE SPILLAGE WAS CLEANED UP AND IS PENDING DISPOSAL.

DRIVER CLAIMS THAT HE PUT TRUCK ON CRUISE CONTROL AND FELL ASLEEP OR PASSED OUT. THE UNIT WENT ACROSS N. BOUND SIDE, THROUGH THE MEDIAN AND ACROSS S.BOUND SIDE. UNIT THEN TRAVELED APPROX 100' INTO A WOODED AREA WHERE TREES STOPPED UNIT AND TRACTOR CAUGHT ON FIRE. SEVERAL TONS OF THE K061 DUST CAME OUT FROM UNDER THE TARP AND SPILLED OVER THE SURROUNDING AREA. TRACTOR AND CONTENTS WERE BURNED IN THE FIRE. DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO HOSPITAL AND TESTED FOR CAUSATION.TEST CAME BACK NEGATIVE. DRIVER WAS RELEASED FROM HOSPITAL. INDUSTRIAL MARINE SERVICES CLEANED UP THE SPILL & VACUUMED REMAINDER OF LOAD FROM TRAILER. DRIVER HAS BEEN DISQUALIFIED UNTIL DOCTORS DETERMINE WHAT CAUSED HIM TO PASS OUT.

column168: TRUCK WAS TRAVELING ON RED RIVER ROAD EN ROUTE TO THE NEXT DELIVERY, MADE A LEFT TURN AND DROVE APPROXIMATELY 50 FEET BEFORE NOTICING THE LOAD BAR WAS IN THE STREET. THE DRIVER PULLED OFF THE ROAD AND THEN SAW A DRUM OF SULFURIC ACID HAD FALLEN OUT OF THE BACK OF THE TRAILER, ROLLED DOWN THE HILL SPILLING LIQUID ON THE ROAD AND ROADSIDE. THE DRIVER NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER, PLACED THE DRUM UPRIGHT AND ATTEMPTED TO CONTROL THE SPILL. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT, POLICE AND HAZMAT TEAM RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND BEGAN THE CLEAN-UP OPERATIONS. A THIRD PARTY EMERGENCY CONTRACTOR, HEPACO WAS SUMMONED TO THE INCIDENT TO CLEAN-UP THE SPILL.

CHECKING LOAD, NOTICE SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL ON TOP OF DRUM, FLOOR AROUND DRUM IS ALSO WET. DART TRUCKING COMPANY, INC, SAFETY DEPARTMENT IS NOTIFIED. CLEAN HARBORS SPECIAL SERVICES IS NOTIFIED OF LEAKING DRUM. A CREW FROM CLEAN HARBORS RESPONDS TO THE SCENE AND PROCEEDS TO LOCATE LEAKING DRUM, TIGHTEN FITTINGS, CLEAN UP FLOOR AROUND DRUM, AND PUT LEAKING DRUM INTO SALVAGE DRUM.

WHEN THE PACKAGE ARRIVED AT OUR STATION IN NEW JERSEY IT WAS THEN NOTICEABLY LEAKING AND WE OPENED IT FINDING 12 BOTTLES OF COLOGNE. AN MSDS WAS OBTAINED AND INDICATED THAT THE FLASHPOINT WAS 63 DEGREES F.  THE FAA WAS CONTACTED AND PACKAGE HELD PENDING INVESTIGATION.

column168: THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP IN THE FEDEX MEMPHIS SORT CENTER BY A MEMBER OF THE SPILL CLEANUP GROUP. CLEANUP AND CONTAINMENT OF THE SPILL WAS DONE PER FEDEX POLICY. THIS WILL BE HELD IN A DANGEROUS GOODS HOLD ROOM UNTIL PACKAGE DISPOSITION INFORMATION HAS BEEN RECEIVED FROM THE SHIPPER.

THIS SHIPMENT WAS BEING OFFLOADED FROM THE COURIER PICKUP VAN IN THE FEDEX WAREHOUSE WHEN TWO OF THE PACKAGES WERE DISCOVERED TO HAVE AN ODOR. UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS (OUTER PACKAGING WAS A BOX), THERE WAS NO DOT CYLINDER OR AEROSOL INSIDE ALTHOUGH THE SHIPMENT WAS SENT AS A FLAMMABLE GAS. THEY HAD CHECKED THE INNER CONTENTS AT MY REQUEST TO SEE IF THERE WAS A VALVE ON A CYLINDER THAT COULD  BE CLOSED. SINCE THIS WAS DECLARED BY THE SHIPPER AS A GAS, WE WERE CONCERNED ABOUT SECURING THIS IN THE STANDARD SALVAGE DRUM DUE TO BUILDUP OF PRESSURE ON THE LID. IT WAS PLACED OUTSIDE AND A THE SHIPPER WAS CONTAINED TO PICK UP THE FREIGHT. THERE WERE THREE OTHER PACKAGES THAT DID NOT APPEAR TO HAVE AN ODOR AT FIRST. I ASKED THE EMPLOYEE TO OPEN ONE AND TELL ME WHAT WAS INSIDE. THE BOX HAD A STRONG ODOR ONCE THEY OPENED IT. INSIDE APPEARED TO BE A PART, AN AIRPLANE FUEL BLADDER WRAPPED IN PLASTIC AND SECURED BY TAPE. THERE APPEARED TO BE SOME DISCREPANCIES WITH THE SHIPMENT. THE ODOR SEEMED TO THE EMPLOYEE TO BE MORE RELATED TO FUEL SO I SUSPECTED A CLASSIFICATION ERROR WHICH SHOULD HAVE BEEN A FLAMMABLE LIQUID. ALSO WHEN THE STATION PERSONNEL CALLED THE SHIPPERS EMERGENCY RESPONSE NUMBER THEY GOT AN ANSWERING MACHINE. THIS WAS BETWEEN 4:30 AND 5:00 P.M. I CALLED AGAIN AFTER RECEIVING THE STATION FAX OF THE SHIPPER'S DANGEROUS GOODS PAPERWORK, AND WHEN I CALLED (800_359-7264 I GOT A MESSAGE TELLING ME THAT I HAD REACHED 1-800 FLY CHEAP AND IT HAD MESSAGES ABOUT PRESSING ONE NUMBER FOR CRUISE INFORMATION, ANOTHER FOR FLIGHT INFORMATION ETC. I THOUGHT I HAD REACHED THE WRONG COMPANY. THEN AGAIN, AFTER 5:00 WE CALLED THE SHIPPER'S MAIN BUSINESS # AGAIN THIS TIME REACHING AN EMPLOYEE. WHEN I QUESTIONED HER ABOUT THE PHONE #'S SHE SAID ALL THEIR NUMBERS WERE ANSWERED BY HER BEFORE 5:00 UNLESS SHE WAS AWAY FROM HER DESK AND THEN THEY ROLL TO AN ANSWERING MACHINE. SHE SAID AT 5:00 SHE FORWARDS THEIR MAIN 800 # (SAME # AS THE ER # THEY GAVE) AND IT ROLLS TO THEIR CUSTOMER SERVICE #. SHE DIDN'T RECOGNIZE THE FLY CHEAP MESSAGE BUT SAID THAT # IS STEVENS. THE EMPLOYEE I SPOKE WITH THERE WAS A KATHY ELLIS.

column168: CSXT EMPLOYEES WERE MOVING A CUT OF CARS IN THE CURTIS BAY YARD.  AS THE CARS WERE BEING MOVED, PRODUCT SLOSHED OUT FROM THE TOP OF PLCX 113028, A TANK CAR LOADED WITH SPENT SULPHURIC ACID.  ONE OF THE EMPLOYEES WAS STANDING NEAR THE CAR WHEN THE PRODUCT SPLASHED ON THE TOP AND DRIPPED DOWN THE SIDE OF THE CAR.  A SMALL AMOUNT OF ACID GOT ON THE EMPLOYEES HAT AND THE SIDE OF HIS FACE.  THE EMPLOYEE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE YARD MASTER AND WENT TO THE YARD OFFICE RESTROOM TO WASH HIS FACE.  AFTER RINSING HIS FACE THE EMPLOYEE REPORTED NO FURTHER SYMPTOMS OR DISCOMFORT.  THE EMPLOYEE RETURNED TO WORK WITHIN THE HOUR.  THE SHIPPER OF THE CAR WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED A TEAM FROM THEIR PLANT.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE FILL-HOLE GASKET HAD DETERIORATED.  APPROXIMATELY 6" OF THE GASKET MATERIAL WAS MISSING.  DUE TO THE MISSING GASKET MATERIAL,  PRODUCT HAD ESCAPED THROUGH THE OPENING BETWEEN THE FILL-HOLE LID AND THE FILL-HOLE NOZZLE.  THE SHIPPER'S TEAM INSTALLED A NEW GASKET AND CLEANED THE TOP AND SIDES OF THE CAR WITH A MIXTURE OF SODA ASH AND WATER.  THE CAR RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER'S FACILITY FOR FURTHER INSPECTION PRIOR TO MOVEMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.

TANK CAR NATX 81053, LOAD OF WASTE FLAMMABLE LIQUID, NOS, WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING LIQUID FROM THE TOP WHEN MOVED AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN RIVERDALE, IL.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED.  THE SHIPPER RESPONDED PERSONEL TO REPAIR THE CAR.  SHIPPER PERSONEL DETERMINED THAT THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE ON TOP OF THE CAR WAS DEFECTIVE.  SHIPPER PERSONNEL MADE REPAIRS, THE LEAK WAS STOPPED, AND THE TANK CAR WAS APPROVED FOR TRANSPORTATION TO DESTINATION.

PLANT OPERATORS WERE ATTEMPTING TO OPEN THE INTERNAL VALVE TO THE FULLY OPENED POSITION. THEY APPLIED STEAM THROUGH THE EXTERNAL VALVE TO WARM UP THE VALVE & PRODUCT. ONCE THE PRODUCT REACHED FLOW TEMPERATURE IT PASSED THROUGH THE PARTIALLY OPENED INTERNAL VALVE AND THROUGH THE OPEN EXTERNAL VALVE AND SPILLED.

DRIVER MADE HOSE AND PUMP CONNECTIONS, BUT FAILED TO ENSURE  BLOW DOWN FITTING WAS CLOSED BEFORE OPENING THE PRODUCT VALVES FOR UNLOADING. PRODUCT WAS RELEASED AND SPILLED THROUGH THE BLOW DOWN VALVE.

FORKLIFT OPERATOR WAS UNLOADING BOXES CONTAINING ORGANIC PEROXIDE PRODUCT AND RAN FORK THROUGH BOX AND PUNCTURED ONE 8 OUNCE PLASTIC CONTAINER.  TERMINAL PERSONNEL QUICKLY CLEANED UP RELEASE WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THE ORGANIC PEROXIDE CONTAMINATED ABSORBENTS WERE PLACED IN A DRUM AND WILL BE DISPOSED OF AT A LATER DATE.

WHILE ON THE DOCK, TERMINAL PERSONNEL DISCOVERED A DAMAGED TWO GALLON CONTAINER OF PRODUCT.  APPARENTLY THE TWO GALLON CONTAINER WAS PUNCTURED BY ADJACENT FREIGHT.  APPROXIMATELY FOUR OUNCES OF PRODUCT RELEASED.  TERMINAL PERSONNEL CONTAINED THE FREE PRODUCT WITH NEUTRALIZER.  THE NEUTRALIZED PRODUCT WAS RECOVERED WITH A BROOM AND DUST PAN.  THE NEUTRALIZED PRODUCT, DAMAGED TWO GALLON CONTAINER AND REMAINING CONTENTS, BROOM AND DUSTPAN AND PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT WERE PLACED INTO A 40 GALLON PLASTIC DRUM.  THE 40 GALLON PLASTIC DRUM IS BEING HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURE WERE REPORTED.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING, TERMINAL PERSONNEL DETECTED AN ODOR.  AREA ISOLATED.  UPON INVESTIGATION BY TERMINAL PERSONNEL, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT A CARTON CONTAIN 20, 1/2 PINT CONTAINERS OF PRODUCT WAS DAMAGED DURING TRANSIT.  THREE, 1/2 PINT CONTAINERS RELEASED APPROXIMATELY ONE PINT OF PRODUCT.  APPARENTLY, THE DAMAGE TO THE CARTON AND CONTAINERS WAS CAUSED BY ADJACENT FREIGHT.  THE CARTON WAS LOCATED AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER AND HAD APPLICABLE LABELING. THE FREE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED TO THE CARTON.  TERMINAL PERSONNEL PLACED THE DAMAGED CARTON CONTAINING 20 ONE PINT CONTAINERS AND PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT INTO A FIVE GALLON RECOVERY DRUM. APPROXIMATELY, 1 TABLESPOON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED AND CONTAINED TO THE LID OF THE DRUM.  APPARENTLY THE DRUM WAS LEAKING DUE TO A LOOSE LID.  TERMINAL PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES AND ABSORBENT.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND FREE PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO A 10 GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE LID WAS TIGHTENED ON THE LEAKING DRUM AND WILL BE FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE. column168: WHILE LOADING, ONE DAMAGED THIRTY GALLON STEEL DRUM WAS DISCOVERED IN THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY EIGHT OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. THE DRUM WILL BE HELD THERE PENDING INSTRUCTIONS FROM THE SHIPPER.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED ON TO THE CONSIGNEE.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: DRESSED IN FULL P.P.E I ATTENDED A SPILL AT DOOR #4 IN THE PRIMARY UNLOAD.  I FOUND A PACKAGE WITH A FLAMMABLE LIQUID DOT DIAMOND LABEL, A DOT 5 - PART LABEL, AND A DAMP BOTTOM WITH A STRONG ODOR. I CONSULTED THE DECISION TREE FOLLOWING ITS JUDGEMENT TO THE FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET.  I ISOLATED THE SPILL, NEUTRALIZED THE ODOR, DNPED THE CONTAMINATED WASTE, RETURNED THE UNCONTAMINATED ITEMS IN A SALVAGE DRUM, AND DECONTAMINATED MY P.P.E.

TECHNICAL NAME, AND UN# WERE COVERED UP.  THE PACKAGE DID NOT HAVE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SHIPPING PAPERS.  DAMAGED PORTION PROCESSED THROUGH D.M.P. PROCESS.

ON FRIDAY, DECEMBER 15, 2000, CSXT PERSONEL IN ROCKPORT, FL , NOTICED RCRX 1425, A LOADED TANK CAR OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID LEAKING FROM THE TOP.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE CONSIGNEE WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  THE CONSIGNEE TEAM FOUND ALL BOLTS ON THE VAPOR FITTING LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT AND LIQUID ON THE SIDE OF THE CAR. column168: A 55 GALLON STEEL DRUM WAS IN STORAGE AT A TEN DAY TRANSFER FACILITY. GATX 7846 WAS RERAILED WITHOUT PROBLEM AND SET OUT ON A SIDING FOR LATER TRANSFER INTO TANKER TRUCKS.  THE ENTIRE LOAD OF IC 769187 WAS LOST IN THE DERAILMENT. ALL OF THE AMMONIA NITRATE WAS RECOVERED AND WAS TRANSPORTED TO BAKERS FARM CO-OP IN BAKER FL FOR SALVAGE.

column168: I WAS CALLED TO RESPOND TO A LEAKER AT CITY CENTER CLERK AREA.  I DONNED MY PPE, AND I FOUND A 5-PART FLAMMABLE LIQUID LEAKER.  THERE WAS BLUE INK ON THE SIDE OF THE BOX WHERE IT HAD LEAKED OUT OF THE CORNER.  I PLACED IT ON A SPILL TUB & REMOVED IT TO HAZMAT/ REWRAP AREA.  INSPECTION SHOWED 1 OF 2 SMALL PAINT CANS LEAKED DUE TO FAILED SEAM ON BOTTOM OF CAN.  WASTE WAS PROCESSED THROUGH DMP PROGRAM, AND SALVAGEABLE PORTION WAS RTS IN A SALVAGE DRUM.

WEARING PROPER PPE I RESPONDED TO SPILL.  I TOOK BACK TO RESPONSE AREA WHERE I DMP'D REMAINING ALCOHOL AND AFFECTED PARTS OF CARTON. I RETURNED REMAINING GALLON OF ALCOHOL IN A YELLOW RETURN TUB.  I DECONTAMINATED MY PPE.

TANK CAR ISOLATED AND APPROPRIATE DEPARTMENTS NOTIFIED.  CN/IC HAZMAT TEAM RESPONDED AND NOTED THAT LADING WAS LEAKING FROM THE WEEP HOLE IN THE WELDED FLANGE OF THE SUMP PLATE. LEAK WAS STOPPED WITH THE USE OF A 3/8 STAINLESS STEEL BOLT.  LADING TRANSLOADED INTO TANK TRUCKS.  SHIPPER APPLIED FOR FRA EXEMPTION TO MOVE TANK CAR TO A REPAIR FACILITY.

TANK CAR ISOLATED AND APPROPRIATE DEPARTMENTS NOTIFIED.  ASHLAND CHEMICAL'S RESPONSE TEAM RESPONDED.  NOTING THAT THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WAS LOOSE, SRV PROPERLY SECURED AND TANK CAR RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

TANK CAR ISOLATED AND APPROPRIATE DEPARTMENTS NOTIFIED.  CN/IC HAZMAT TEAM RESPONDED AND FOUND RUPTURED DISC ASSEMBLY HAD RECENTLY BEEN CHANGED OUT (THE OLD ASSEMBLY WAS STILL CHANGED TO THE RAIL CAR) AND VAPOR WAS ESCAPING FROM BETWEEN THE TEFLON GASKET AND THE DISC RETAINING RING.  ALSO, THREE BOLTS TO THE ASSEMBLY WERE NOT TOOL TIGHT.  BSAF'S RESPONSE TEAM TIGHTENED THE BOLTS AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  TANK CAR WAS RELEASED TO THE CONSIGNEE.

WHILE UNLOADING, TERMINAL PERSONNEL DETECTED A STRONG ODOR COMING FROM THE TRAILER.  THE AREA WAS ISOLATED AND CONSOLIDATED WASTE INDUSTRIES OF MONTCLAIR, CA RESPONDED TO INVESTIGATE.  UPON INVESTIGATION, SEVEN, FIVE GALLON PLASTIC PAILS WERE DISCOVERED LEAKING IN THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED TO THE TOP OF THE PAILS.  APPARENTLY THE PAILS WERE LEAKING DUE TO LOOSE LIDS.  CONSOLIDATED WASTE INDUSTRIES PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND ABSORBENTS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND FREE PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO A 10 GALLON RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE DISPOSED OF BY CONSOLIDATED WASTE INDUSTRIES. column168: PUNCTURE OF DRUM WITH FORKLIFT BLADE HAD TO OCCUR SOMETIME DURING UNLOADING OFF CITY TRAILER ONTO OUR TRAILER.  THE DRUM HAS A PUNCTURE HOLE APPROX. 2" FROM BOTTOM OF DRUM, BUT THE DRUM HAD OTHER DRUMS BEHIND IT WHEN LOADED ON OUR VAN.  ALSO, ALL THE DRUMS HAD CARDBOARD UNDER AND AROUND THEM.

ON 12-14-00, 1800 HOURS, TRENT SHORT (CITY DSR) INFORMED ME HE HAD HAZARDOUS MATERIALS LEAKING FROM A DRUM ON CITY DELIVERY TRAILER. WE IDENTIFIED MATERIAL AND ISOLATED, CLEANED UP RESIDUE &  PLACED PUNCTURED DRUM IN SALVAGE CONTAINER.  INVESTIGATION INTO HOW DRUM WAS DAMAGED IS UNDERWAY.
NO REMARKS.

column168: DRIVER FINISHED UNLOADING.  CAPPED HOSE.  DRIVER TRIPPED AND THE CAP ON THE HOSE HIT A CONCRETE LEDGE AND BROKE.
DRIVERS PUMP STARTED TO LEAK.  SOME PRODUCT MISSED THE BUCKET.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ROAD CONDITIONS AT THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT WERE WET.  DRIVER OF OUR TRUCK WAS CUT OFF BY ANOTHER DRIVER WHILE ON THE FREEWAY. IMMEDIATELY AFTER CUTTING DRIVER OFF, VEHICLE SLOWED DOWN.  TRUCK DRIVER TRIED TO AVOID HITTING OTHER VEHICLE BY MOVING TO SHOULDER OF ROAD.  THE COMBINATION OF THIS SUDDEN MOVEMENT, WET AND MUDDY SHOULDER, AND SHIFTING OF LIQUID IN DRUMS CAUSED VEHICLE TO TIP ON ITS SIDE.

DRIVER STARTED UNLOADING INTO STORAGE TANK BEFORE HE CHECKED IN AT OFFICE.  HE ASSUMED THAT BECAUSE THEY ORDERED 5000 GAL. IT WOULD FIT INTO THE TANK.  IT DID NOT AND APPROXIMATELY 250 GAL. RAN OVER THROUGH VENT BEFORE DRIVER SHUT OFF THE PUMP.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED IN CONCRETE CONTAINMENT.  A VACUUM TRUCK WAS CALLED AND PUMPED OUT CONCRETE CONTAINMENT.  DRIVER WAS ADVISED OF DRY FORK MINE POLICY OF CHECKING IN BEFORE UNLOADING.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: THE TRANSPORT VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING NORTHBOUND ONE MILE SOUTH OF ELGIN, OKLAHOMA, ON THE H.E. BAILEY TURNPIKE (I-44).  THE TRANSPORT VEHICLE VEERED TO THE RIGHT INTO A SNOW COVERED SHOULDER.  THE DRIVER TRIED TO BRING THE TRANSPORT BACK ONTO THE TRAVEL PORTION OF THE ROADWAY.  THE TRANSPORT VEHICLE WENT INTO BROAD SLIDE AND OVERTURNED 1/2 TIMES AND CAME TO REST ON THE PASSENGER'S SIDE OF THE TRANSPORT.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: OUR VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING EAST ON E.W. ROAD #51. THE DRIVER STATED AS HE WAS ENTERING A LEFT HAND CURVE, THE TRAILER RIGHT WHEELS ENTERED THE BAR DITCH, CAUSING HIM TO LOSE CONTROL AND  THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER ROLLED UP ON THE PASSENGER SIDE AND COMING TO REST ON THE PASSENGER SIDE.  THE ROLLOVER CAUSED DAMAGE TO THE TRAILER AND THE LOSS OF 3100 GALLONS OF PRODUCT.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: PLASTIC DRUM WAS LOAD BY SHIPPER ON A SUB PAR PALLET WITH NAILS BENTOVER & STICKING UP.  1 NAIL FINALLY PUNCTURED THROUGH ONE OF THE PAIL (DRUM).  CHECKED ERG BOOK, ALERTED PERSONEL ON DOCK.  CALLED THE HAZMAT CLEAN-UP CREW.  CALLED SHIPPER TO ALERT THEM OF SITUATION AND HOW TO AVOID IT BY USING HIGHER QUALITY PALLETS.

A TRAILER OF PACKAGES WAS BEING UNLOADED AT THE ALLEGIANCE FACILITY. A PALLET OF PACKAGES WAS REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER AND PLACED IN A STAGING AREA INSIDE THE FACILITY FOR RELOADING ONTO A DIFFERENT TRAILER.  WHILE WITHIN THE STAGING AREA, THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR OBSERVED SLIGHT LEAKAGE FROM ONE DAMAGED PACKAGE.  THE TRAILER WAS INSPECTED TO DETERMINE IF THERE WAS ANY SPILLAGE DURING TRANSPORT AND NONE WAS DETECTED IN THE TRAILER.  FACILITY PERSONNEL TRAINED IN RESPONDING TO INCIDENTAL SPILLS UTILIZED ABSORBENT PADS FOR CLEANUP. THE DAMAGED BOX AND THE ABSORBENT MATERIAL USED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL WAS PLACED IN A DOT CERTIFIED DRUM AND MOVED TO THE HAZARDOUS WASTE STORAGE AREA FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  EMPLOYEES WERE RESTRICTED FROM THE IMMEDIATE AREA UNTIL CLEANUP WAS COMPLETED.  NO OTHER PRODUCT WAS AFFECTED.  TOTAL SPILL VOLUME WAS 1 GALLON.  THIS INCIDENT IS REPORTABLE DUE TO THE PACKAGE BEING COVERED BY AN ACTIVE SHIPPING PAPER.  ACTIONS TAKEN TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS:  THE FACILITY HAS A FORKLIFT OPERATOR TRAINING AND LICENSING PROGRAM IN PLACE.  NO ADDITIONAL ACTIONS WERE IDENTIFIED AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT.

column168: WHILE TRANSFERRING SHIPMENT AT TM DOCK, WORKER DAN HAY NOTICED SLOW LEAK IN ONE DRUM.  2-3 TBSP MATL LOST, EVAPORATED SOAKED INTO TRL FLOOR.  DRUM PUT IN SALVAGE DRUM AND RET TO SHIPPER.

TRAILER 206920 ARRIVED INTO MILWAUKEE.  TOTES ON REAR OF TRAILER. TRAILER DOOR OPENED AND FOUND THE LID OFF OF BUNG-TOP OF TOTE WET, PRODUCT RUNNING DOWN SIDE.  OTHER FREIGHT ON TRAILER SPLASHED WITH MATERIAL.  CEILING AND FLOOR OF TRAILER EQUALLY WET.  CHEMICAL CLEANUP COMPANY CALLED IN TO CLEAN UP TRAILER, TIGHTEN LID, AND EVALUATE REST OF FREIGHT.  PRODUCT SENT OUT FOR DELIVERY ON 12-15. ALL OTHER PRODUCT SENT OUT FOR DELIVERY.
DRIVER HAD SMALL SPILL WHILE MAKING A DELIVERY TO STORAGE TANK. DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED SPILL.  IT WAS CONTAINED TO PAVEMENT AND CLEANED UP.  NO WATERWAYS WERE AFFECTED.

DRIVER DID NOT CALCULATE STRAPPING CORRECTLY AND OVERFILLED TANK COMPARTMENT WHILE LOADING.  WE IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN THE PUMP AND CLOSED ALL VALVES TO TRAILER AND TANK AND PUT DOWN ABSORBANT TO CONTAIN SPILL.  ONCE SPILL WAS CONTAINED WE BEGAN THE CLEANUP.  WE SWEPT UP THE ABSORBANT AND PUT IT INTO 2 OVERPACK DRUMS.  THE FOLLOWING MORNING I CONDUCTED A SAFETY MEETING WITH ALL DRIVERS AND WAREHOUSE PERSONEL AND DISCUSSED WHAT HAPPENED AND HOW TO PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING AGAIN.  ONE OF THE THINGS WE ARE DOING NOW IS TO HAVE AN ADDITIONAL PERSON ASSISTS IN LOADING AND CHECKING STRAPPING. NRC WAS IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED.

column168: SHIPMENT ARRIVED AT THE UPH DOCK WITH ANOTHER SKID ON TOP OF IT. THE SKID ON TOP WAS OVERLAPPING THE 5 GALLON PAILS AND PUNCTURED THE TOP PAIL OF GUN CLEANER.  THE PUNCTURED 5 GALLON PAIL WAS PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND PUT IN THE HAZMAT BAY FOR DISPOSAL.

PRODUCT WAS BEING UNLOADED FROM THE CARGO TANK TO THE CUSTOMERS STORAGE TANK WHEN A TRANSFER HOSE BECAME DISCONNECTED FROM THE STORAGE TANK. DRIVER WAS ABLE TO IMMEDIATELY STOP THE FLOW OF PRODUCT RESULTING IN APPROXIMATELY 3 GALLONS OF PRODUCT BEING RELEASED. A MAJORITY OF THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED IN THE SPILL BOX ON TOP OF THE STORAGE TANK. A SMALL AMOUNT (LESS THAN A GALLON) DID DRAIN FROM THE STORAGE TANK ONTO A CONCRETE PAD. ALL OF THE PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP FOR DISPOSAL BY PLANT PERSONNEL. NO FURTHER CONSEQUENCES RESULTED FROM THE INCIDENT.

AS A RESULT OF THE COLLISION, A BOLT PROTRUDING FROM THE RAIL CAR RIPPED A TEAR IN THE SIDE OF OUR CARGO TANK NEAR THE REAR SEAM/WELD OF OUR CARGO PULL-TRAILER. 232 GALLONS OF DYED DIESEL FURL#2 WAS SPILLED ONTO THE ROADWAY AND SHOULDER AREA BEFORE WE COULD CONTROL AND SPILL AND TRANSFER THE PRODUCT ONTO ANOTHER CARGO TANK. AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE AND ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR WERE DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE TO ADDRESS THE ENVIRONMENTAL ISSUE OF THE SPILLED DIESEL.

column168: DURING THE TANSPORT TO THE DRIVER'S FACILITY, A DRUM SHIFTED POSITION AND SCRAPPED AGAINST A BOLT IN THE WALL OF THE TRUCK. THE SPILL WAS DISCOVERED WHEN THE TRUCK ARRIVED AT THE FACILITY AND ALL OF IT WAS CONTAINED IN THE BACK OF THE TRUCK.  THE LEAKING DRUM WAS OVERPACKED INTO A 85- GALLON SALVAGE DRUM.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH AN ABSORBENT AND CONTAINERIZED INTO THE 85- GALLON SALVAGE DRUM.

OUR DRIVER WAS DISPATCHED TO PICK UP A LOAD OF HAZARDOUS WASTE AT THE ONYX FACILITY.  THE TRAILER WAS PRELOADED BY ONYX PERSONNEL PRIOR TO ARRIVAL OF OUR DRIVER.  DURING A ROUTINE VEHICLE INSPECTION BY OUR DRIVER ON I-40 NEAR HOLBROOK AZ, A LEAKING DRUM WAS DETECTED. THE DRIVER DONNED PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT, SEALED THE LEAK WITH SILICONE CAULK AND A SCREW, AND PLACED ABSORBANT ON THE FLOOR OF THE VAN.  THE DRIVER PROCEEDED TO THE HOLBROOK TRUCK PLAZA TO WAIT FOR THE RESPONSE CONTRACTOR.  THE RESPONSE CONTRACTOR OVERPACKED THE DRUM AND CLEANED THE VAN FLOOR WHEREBY THE DRIVER CONTINUED TO HIS DESTINATION.  NO WASTE EXITED THE TRAILER.  THE HOLE IN THE DRUM WAS DESCRIBED BY OUR DRIVER AS APPROXIMATELY 1/8" IN DIAMETER JUST BELOW THE FIRST RING ON THE DRUM.

column168: TEAM DRIVER CHECKED HIS VEHICLE AT THE COMPLETION OF A REST BREAK AND FOUND HE HAD LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  HE INVESTIGATED AND FOUND TWO DRUMS SECURED AT THE TAIL OF THE TRAILER. THE BUNGS WERE LYING ON THE HEADS OF THE DRUMS.  THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO REPLACE THE BUNGS TO STOP ANY FURTHER RELEASE.  HE DRIVER STATED THAT THE LIQUID SQUIRTED OUT OF THE TOP OF THE DRUMS AND HAD SPLASHED THE PALLETIZED FREIGHT NEXT TO THEM.  THE MATERIAL IS PERFUME AND IS EXTREMELY SMELLY.  ADDITIONALLY, THE MATERIAL IS OIL BASED AND THE LIQUID THAT LEAKED OUT OF THE TRAILER SPRAYED ALL OVER THE BACK DOORS AND THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  AFTER DETERMINING THAT THERE WAS NO FURTHER RISK, THE CARRIERS HAZMAT TECHNICIAN DIRECTED THE DRIVER TO A SPILL CONTRACTOR IN EL PASO, TEX.  WHEN THE VEHICLE ARRIVED AT THE CONTRACTOR, THE PALLET THAT HAD BEEN SPLASHED WAS REMOVED AND REWRAPPED.  AFTER THE CONTRACTOR DETERMINED THAT NO OTHER FREIGHT HAD BEEN CONTAMINATED, THE VEHICLE CONTINUED AND COMPLETED DELIVERY WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

DOWN FROM HIS SPILL KIT TO SOAK UP THE SPILLAGE.  INITIALLY, THE CONSIGNEE WOULD NOT ACCEPT THE DRUM.  A SUPERVISOR INSPECTED IT AND DECIDED THAT THEY WOULD TAKE IT AND PUT IT INTO THEIR PROCESS IMMEDIATELY.  IT WAS ACCEPTED WITH A DAMAGE NOTATION.  THE CONSIGNEE ALSO DISPOSED OF THE CLEAN UP MATERIALS.

AT THE CARRIER'S FACILITY A PORTABLE TANK WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING FROM THE VICINITY OF A SUPPORT LEG.  THE SPILLAGE WAS CONFINED TO THE TRAILER AND A FEW PUDDIES ON THE BLACKTOP UNDERNEATH THE TRAILER.  THE TANK WAS ABOUT 1/4 FULL, DRIPPING SLOWLY.  THE PRODUCT WAS COAGULATING AROUND THE LEAK AREA.  DOCK PERSONNEL HAD PLACED ABSORBENT ON THE SPILLAGE ON THE TRAILER AND SET THE TANK ON A SPILL CATCH BASIN.  THERE HAD BEEN NO EXPOSURES.  CARRIER'S HAZMAT TECHNICIAN NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER.  THEIR RESPONSE COORDINATOR CONCURRED THAT THE ACTIONS TAKEN WERE PROPER AND SUFFICIENT TO CONTROL THE INCIDENT UNTIL THE ARRIVAL OF A SPILL CONTRACTOR.  THE SHIPPER THEN RETAINED THE SERVICES OF A CONTRACTOR TO PERFORM ANY NECESSARY CLEAN UP AND TO SECURE THE LEAKING TANK.

Clean Harbors Environmental Services shoveled up the loose product and repackaged the damaged cartons. TRUCK TRACTOR IS EQUIPPED WITH A POWER TAKE OFF (PTO) PUMP.  THE PUMP IS EQUIPPED WITH A "T" UNLOADING FROM BOTH SIDES OF CAB OF TRUCK.  IN THIS CASE, DRIVER WAS UNLOADING FROM THE DRIVER'S SIDE OF CAB.  THE DRIVER WAS ON DRIVER'S SIDE OF CAB TO OBSERVE CUSTOMER'S BULK TANK TO PREVENT OVER FILLING & TO CONTROL PTO CLUTCH.  AS HE WAS OBSERVING THE UNLOADING PROCESS, THE CAP ON THE PASSENGER SIDE OF THE UNLOADING "T" VIBRATED LOOSE WHICH ALLOWED DIESEL FUEL TO BE DISPERSED ON THE GRAVEL PARKING LOT.  CAPS ARE SECURED VIA CAM LOCKS & VELCROW STRAPS.  WE CONTAINED THE PRODUCT ON THE PARKING LOT & HIRED ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD SERVICES TO CLEAN UP, HAUL DIRT/ROCK TO SEDALIA LANDFILL, REPLACE FRESH ROCK.  WE NOW HAVE ALL TRUCK PTO PIPES EQUIPPED WITH BALL VALVES ALONG W/CAPS TO PREVENT FUTURE LOSES.

column42: HYDROFLUORIC ACID, WITH MORE THAN 60 PERCENT STRENGTH
column168: SOLVAY FLOURIDES PRODUCES VARIOUS CONCENTRATIONS OF HYDROFLUORIC ACID. MOST OF THE HYDROFLUORIC ACID IS PUT INTO DOT MC 312 TANK TRAILERS AND SHIPPED TO OUR CUSTOMERS.  ON NOVEMBER 29, 2000 AT 10:55 HOURS THE SOLVAY FLUORIDES TANK TRAILER NO. 86251 WAS LOADED WITH OF 49% HYDROFLUORIC ACID. THIS TANK TRAILER HELD APPROXIMATELY 4200 GALLONS (OR 40302 LBS.) OF 49% WT. HYDROFLUORIC ACID.  IT WAS LOADED AS A SPARE TANK TRAILER.  A SPARE LOADED 49% HYDROFLUORIC ACID TRAILER IS KEPT SO WE CAN PROVIDE ON-TIME TO OUR CUSTOMERS.  LOADED TRAILERS ARE KEPT IN A ROCK COVERED CONCRETE SLAB LOT ON THE SOUTH SIDE OF THE PLANT.  LOADED TRAILERS IN THE LOT ARE VISUALLY INSPECTED DAILY AROUND 7 TO 8 AM EVERY MORNING AND WHENEVER ANY EMPLOYEES ARE IN THE AREA. TRAILER NO. 86251 WAS NOT OBSERVED LEAKING ON ANY OF THE MORNING VISUAL INSPECTIONS.  TRAILER NO. 86251 WAS OBSERVED LEAKING AT 1400 HOURS ON DECEMBER 2, 2000.  THE MATERIAL WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TRAILER.  A TOTAL OF 137 GALLONS OF 49% HYDROFLUORIC ACID WAS RELEASED TO THE GROUND WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA ASH, BY THE COMPANY'S ON-SITE EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM, TO FORM 1350 LBS. OF SODIUM FLUORIDE.  THE SODIUM FLUORIDE WAS WASHED TO THE PLANT'S SEWER SUMP,  AFTER OBTAINING APPROVAL TO DO SO BY THE LOCAL POTW, AMERICAN BOTTOMS. UPON INSPECTION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE LEAK OCCURRED IN THE BOTTOM OF THE TRAILER DUE TO A PINHOLE IN THE TANK.  THE PINHOLE WAS THE RESULT OF HYDROFLUORIC ACID CORROSION OF THE TRAILER LINING AND THE HULL OF THE TANK. TO PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING AGAIN SOLVAY TANK TRAILERS WERE EQUIPPED WITH CORROSION SENSORS.

ONE OF OUR DRIVERS, JACK FUNK, WAS IN THE PROCESS OF UNLOADING A TANKER OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTION TO OHIO POOLS IN STRONGSVILLE,  OHIO.  THE UNLOADING HOSE SPRUNG A LEAK JACK IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF ALL THE VALVES TO STOP THE LEAK.

OUR DRIVER WAS ON UNLOADING RACK BEING DRUMMED OFF.  HE WAS SITTING IN THE TRUCK, LOOKED BEHIND HIM, THOUGHT UNLOADER WAS FINISHED, SO HE WAS GOING TO THE BACK OF THE TRUCK.  WHEN HE GOT TO THE BACK OF TRUCK OPERATOR WAS UNHOOKING THE HOSE AND WHEN HE PULLED ON THE HOSE IT SPRAYED OUR DRIVER JIMMY PRICE IN THE FACE, NECK AND CHEST.  THE BLEED OFF VALVE WAS STOPPED UP ON THE FITTING AND LEFT PRESSURE IN THE LINE.  OUR DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO EAST JEFFERSON HOSPITAL IN NEW ORLEANS, & SEEN BY DR. CHERYDEN ROBERT.

column168: FILE:2105 F AND 2105 D, SHIPPER:UVEX SAFETY, INC., AWB# PVD 7578848535 ANC. ON 12/01/2000 AT 0007 AN ODOR WAS REPORTED IN BUILDING D OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177.  PART TIME HAZ MAT TECHNICIAN CHRISTOPHOR CHAPPU DONNED PROPER PERSONNEL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL HE FOUND A BROWN FIBERBOARD WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGING.  HE OPENED THIS PACKAGE AND BEGAN HIS INVESTIGATION.  UPON THIS INVESTIGATION HE FOUND THE FOLLOWING REGULATED ITEMS; 8 X 16 OUNCE PLASTIC RECEPTACLES WITH PLASTIC PUMP TYPE DISPENSERS THAT HAD A PLASTIC SNAP ON TOP, UVEX CLEAR LENS CLEANING STATIONS. ONE OF THESE RECEPTACLES LEAKED ITS ENTIRE CONTENTS DUE TO LOOSE CLOSURE.  NONE OF THE LIDS HAD POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE, CAUSING THE SPILLAGE.  THESE "STATIONS" HAVE PAPER TOWELS SURROUNDING THE PLASTIC RECEPTACLE.  THESE WERE PACKAGED IN FIBERBOARD BOXES BEST DESCRIBED AS MANUFACTURES PACKAGING.  ALL OF THESE CLEANING STATIONS WERE INSIDE ON FIBERBOARD BOX, WITH NO ABSORBENT MATERIAL SURROUNDING THE SIX INNER BOXES. HE REPLACE THE ITEMS BACK INTO THE BOX, RESEALED IT AND PLACED IT INTO 2 PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  HE PLACED THE BAGGED SHIPMENT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND PLACED THE RECOVERY DRUM IN THE HAZ MAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION. THE AREA INVOLVED WITH ODOR WAS WELL VENTILATED BEFORE NORMAL WORK OPERATIONS WERE RESUMED, AND THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED TO THE OUTER PACKAGING.  THERE WAS ONE EMPLOYEE IN CONTACT WITH ODOR.  HE WAS ADVISED WHAT IT WAS AND RETURNED TO HIS WORK AREA.  NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED, NO CHANGES IN THE EMPLOYEE.  NO FOLLOW UP NEEDED. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS, OR A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THE CONTENT WERE A REGULATED MATERIAL. THERE ARE PICTURES OF THIS SHIPMENT ON FILE IN THE ILN HAZ MAT OFFICE. CLEAR OF ACENE 0029.

AT 1420HRS ON 12-7-00, CTS MGR LERCH WAS CONTACTED BY CHEYENNE 1-SPOT CARMAN AND ADVISED THAT AN ODOR OF AMMONIA COULD BE DETECTED COMING FROM TANK CAR PLMX 2548.  UPON RECEIVING INFORMATION, MGR LERCH ADVISED CAR DEPARTMENT TO MOVE CAR OUTSIDE FOR FURTHER HANDLING.  INSPECTION OF CAR BY MGR LERCH REVEALED SLIGHT RELEASE OF RESIDUE VAPOR FROM THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE.  UPON DETERMINING SOURCE OF LEAK, MGR LERCH CONTACTED SHIPPER, COASTAL CHEMICAL AND SPOKE TO DEB BLISS, RAIL COORDINATOR.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE THEN MADE TO HAVE RESCAR MOBIL RAIL CAR SERVICE REPAIR THE CAR.  ON 12-8-00, DON SHRIVER OF RESCAR REPLACED THE O-RINGS IN THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE, WHICH STOPPED THE RELEASE OF RESIDUE VAPOR.  CAR WAS THEN BILLED TO A REPAIR SHOP FOR FURTHER INSPECTION AND HANDLING.  THERE WERE DRAINS OR WATERWAYS AFFECTED AS THE RESULT OF THIS RELEASE. AT ABOUT 1425 HOURS OF WEDNESDAY, 12/20/00, CONTAINER SNIU 121122, A LOAD OF ETHYL BENZENE WAS PRESENTED AT THE GATE OF THE UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD INTERMODAL RAMP AT AVONDALE, LA.  THE CONTAINER WAS INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE DRIPPING A SMALL AMOUNT OF ITS CONTENTS FROM THE TOP OF THE CONTAINER.  UNION PACIFIC RAMP PERSONNEL REJECTED THE SHIPMENT AND INSTRUCTED THE DRIVER TO RETURN IT TO THE SHIPPER FOR SECUREMENT.  THE DRIVER LEFT THE GATE AREA AND ABANDONED THE CONTAINER ON ITS CHASSIS AT THE END OF THE RAMP DRIVEWAY AT AVONDALE GARDEN ROAD.  DUE TO ITS PROXIMITY TO THE RAILROAD MAINLINE, THE MAINLINE WAS SHUT DOWN FROM 1620 HOURS UNTIL 1720 HOURS.  NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO UNION PACIFIC SPECIAL AGENT TOMMY CARMICHAEL, THE SHIPPER - EVERGREEN AMERICA, THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE, THE LOUISIANA DEPT. OF ENV. QUALITY AND UNION PACIFIC MANAGER OF ENV.FIELD OPERATIONS, T.M. ROBINSON.  UPON BEING ABANDONED THE LEAKAGE WAS REPORTED TO HAVE STOPPED.  SPECIAL AGENT CARMICHAEL RESPONDED AND MET WITH PERSONNEL FROM OIL MOP INC., A CONTRACTOR DISPATCHED BY THE SHIPPER.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE CONTAINER WAS MISSING A MANWAY GASKET.  THE GASKET WAS REPLACED AND THE SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID THAT HAD DRIPPED ONTO THE GROUND WAS CLEANED UP USING SORBENT MATERIALS.  THE CONTAINER WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER FOR FURTHER INSPECTION.  ALL OF THE CLEAN UP MATERIALS GENERATED WERE REMOVED BY OIL MOP INC. FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  AT THE TIME OF THE RELEASE, UNION PACIFIC WAS NOT THE CARRIER, HOWEVER, THIS REPORT IS BEING FILED TO COMPLY WITH THE REGULATORY REPORTING REQUIREMENT IN 49CFR 171 16  (A).

column168: TRACTION AND BEGAN SLIDING BACKWARDS. HE REPORTED THAT HE ATTEMPTED TO "FEATHER" THE BRAKES IN ORDER TO STOP THE SLIDE AND GAIN CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE. DURING THIS ATTEMPT. THE FRONT WHEELS BEGAN TO SLIDE IN A COUNTER-CLOCKWISE DIRECTION. THE TRACK THEN SLID DOWNHILL APPROXIMATELY, 120 FEET BACKWARDS AND TO THE RIGHT UNTIL IT CROSSED A SMALL DITCH (APPROXIMATELY FOUR FEET WIDE AND ONE FOOT DEEP) AND STRUCK A STEEP EMBANKMENT. THE  INITIAL CONTACT WITH THE EMBANKMENT WAS WITH THE RIGHT REAR OF THE TRUCK. THE RIGHT REAR DECK DUG INTO THE EMBANKMENT ABOUT TWO FEET WHICH PROBABLY PREVENTED A ROLLOVER. CHRIS STATED THAT HE IMMEDIATELY EXITED THE CAB AND THE TRUCK WAS ALREADY BURNING. HE CALLED FOR HELP RIGHT AWAY. DURING THE MOST INTENSE BURING, WE WERE UNABLE TO MAKE ANY DETERMINATION AS TO THE SOURCE. HOWEVER, ON TUESDAY 12/19/00, WE WERE ABLE TO SEE THE SOURCE OF THE BLAZE. IT APPEARS THAT THE CONTACT BROKE THE GAS LINE BETWEEN THE FLO-METER AND THE TOTALIZER COMPARTMENT WHEN THE BELLY VALVE, FLO-MATIC AND ALL BALL VALVES WERE FINALLY SHUT OFF, IT DID NOT STOP THE FIRE. DAMAGE TO THE VEHICLE INCLUDES EVERYTHING ON THE REAR DECK BURNED AWAY THE RIGHT REAR DECK BENT UPWARD AND ELECTRICAL COMPONETS FROM THE REAR TO THE FRONT WERE ALSO BURNED. THERE APPEARED TO BE NO OTHER PROPERLY DAMAGE OTHER THAN A GAUGE IN THE EMBANKMENT AND A BURNED SMALL FIR TREE. CHRIS JACOBS WAS UNINJURED, BUT WAS SENT FOR A DRUG ALCOHOL SCREEN.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY ICTF SECURITY, REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE ICTF AND LOCATED THE ABOVE CONTAINER IN YELLOW ROW, SPACE 194.  A SMALL POOL OF LIQUID WAS ON THE PAVEMENT NEAR THE CHASSIS LANDING GEAR.  THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK WHERE IT COULD BE PROPERLY SECURED AND ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION.  UPON OPENING THE REAR DOORS, DEVELOPED THE CONTENTS TO BE LARGE 275 GALLON POLY TOTES.  THE TOTES WERE LOADED SIDE BY SIDE FROM THE NOSE OF THE REAR FOR 4 ROWS, AND A SINGLE TOTE PLACED ON THE CENTER FLOOR AT THE DOORS.  A PIECE OF 2X4 WAS NAILED TO THE FLOOR AT THE REAR TOTE AND USED PALLETS WERE PLACED TO THE SIDES TO PROTECT AGAINS LATERAL MOVEMENT.  THIS IS NOT A RECOMMENDE PROTOCOL FOR THE SECUREMENT OF THIS STYLE OF TOTE, NOR IS IT AN APPROVED METHOD PER THE ARR BOE6C.  THE TOTE AT THE REAR DOOR HAD 2 CRACKS, APPROXIMATELY 3 INCHES LONG, ONE AT EACH TOP CORNER OF THE TOTE.  THERE WAS NO CONTACT WITH THE OTHER TOTES AT THIS LOCATION, AND IT APPEARS THE LIQUID SURGING DURING TRANSIT CAUSED THE TOTE TO FLEX AND CRACK.  APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS LOST FROM THIS TOTE.  THE TOTE IN THE RIGHT FRONT CORNER OF THE CONTAINER HAD THE SAME TYPE OF CRACKS AND IT APPEARS APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS LOST DURING TRANSIT.  CLOSER INSPECTION OF THE TOTES DEVELOPED 6 OF THE 7 WERE RECONDITIONED, AND MISSING THE INSPECTION DATE STAMP.  THE PRODUCT FROM THE 2 DAMAGED TOTES WAS TRANSFERRED TO NEW TOTES, ALONG WITH THE PRODUCT FROM THE OTHER 4 OUT OF SPEC TOTES.  THE CONTAINER FLOOR WAS CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE, AND THE NEW TOTES PLACED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER.  THE LADING WAS PROPERLY SECURED AND RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.

HISTORY OF MORRISON SPILL.  ON NOVEMBER 1, 2000 UNITED PROPANE SERVICES PURCHASED THE ASSETS OF AGWAY ENERGY PRODUCTS OF BROOKVILLE, PA, INCLUDING THEIR CUSTOMER BASE AND CUSTOMER FILES.  MR. MORRISON WAS A FUEL OIL CUSTOMER OF AGWAY'S AND WAS ON THEIR LIST OF "AUTOMATIC KEEP FULL" CUSTOMERS.  BECAUSE OF THESE RECORDS WE DISPATCHED A FUEL DELIVERY TRUCK TO THE MORRISON RESIDENCE TO FILL THEIR FUEL OIL TANK.  EARLIER IN THE YEAR MR. MORRISON CHANGED HIS HEATING SYSTEM FROM FUEL OIL TO PROPANE AND REMOVED HIS INSIDE OIL STORAGE TANK.  UNFORTUNATELY MR. MORRISON DID NOT REMOVE HIS FILL AND VENT PIPES WHICH EXTENDED FROM THE INSIDE OF HIS BASEMENT TO THE EXTERIOR OF HIS HOME WHERE THEY REMAINED IN THE SAME PLACE AND CONDITION AS THEY DID FOR MANY YEARS.  WHEN OUR DRIVER STOPPED AT THE MORRISON RESIDENCE HE PROCEEDED TO PUMP OIL INTO THE FILL PIPE ON THE EXTERIOR OF THE MORRISON HOME AND STOPPED HEN MR.  MORRISON CAME OUT AND TOLD HIM THE PRODUCT WAS FLOWING ONTO HIS BASEMENT FLOOR.  THE DRIVER STOPPED IMMEDIATELY AND NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR WHO INSTITUTED A UNITED CLEANUP AND CALLED AN INDEPENDENT CLEANUP FIRM FOR ASSISTANCE.  MR. MORRISON'S BASEMENT HAS A FLOOR DRAIN THAT EMPTIES INTO HIS "FARM POND" AND WHEN THE DRIVER REALIZED THIS HE TOOK MEASURES TO CONTAIN THE OIL IN THE INLET AREA OF THE POND.  AS SOON AS THE SUPERVISOR HAD DISPATCHED CLEANUP PERSONNEL HE CALLED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, PA.  DEP AND LOCAL EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT.

JEFF SLOWED THE VEHICLE DOWN, THE TANK BROKE LOOSE AND ROLLED OVER ON ITS SIDE, ON THE SIDE OF THE HIGHWAY. THE VALVES ON THE TANK POPPED OFF CAUSING ANHYDROUS TO ESCAPE. JEFF NOTIFIED THE OFFICE BY CELL PHONE, THE ASSISTANT MANAGER RESPONDED IMMEDIATELY. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT AND SHERIFF OFFICE WERE NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. THE RELEASE WAS OVER IN 20 MINUTES. AFTER THE ACCIDENT IT WAS DISCOVERED THE WELD ON THE TONGUE WAS BROKE. THE ANHYDROUS TANKS, AND TONGUE WELDS ARE CHECKED AS THEY LEAVE THE FACILITIES.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: DEC. 27/2000@14;44 UNIT#301127, TRIS39224&P LOADED 34510 KGS. OF AMMONIUM NITRATE(34-0-0-1. SIMPLOT#20794  PHB#02-111163. THIS UNIT WAS OPERATED BY DAVID ANDREY(#3135) & DAVID HILL (#2845). DAVID ANDREY DROVE THE FIRST SHIFT FROM BRANDON TO RAYMOND MT.(BORDER).  UPON DEPARTURE DAVE NOTED THE ROADS WERE CLEAR TO REDVERS.  REDVERS TO WEYBURN THE VISIBILITY WAS DOWN, NOT BAD.  THERE WAS VISIBLE SIGNS OF OCCASIONAL SNOW PACK.  WITHIN THESE AREAS MEETING VEHICLES OFFERED O VISIBILITY.  WEYBURN TO PANGMAN WAS GOOD. WITHIN 5 MILES OF PANGMAN ROADS WERE CLEAR, FROM THERE TO THE BORDER THE ROADS WERE SNOW PACKED. AT THE BORDER THE WEATHER WAS WARM ENOUGH TO WEAR T-SHIRT WHITE STRETCHING & CUSTOMS RELATED WORK.  UPON DEPARTURE FROM THE BORDER DAVE ANDREY WENT INTO THE BUNK & DOES NOT KNOW THE TYPE OF ROAD CONDITIONS.  HE THINKS AT ONE TIMES HE WAS MOMENTARILY AWARE THE ROAD SPEED WAS SLOWER, BUT THERE WAS NO INDICATION THERE WAS ANY PROBLEM AS HE WENT RIGHT BACK TO SLEEP.  A PERIOD OF TIME LATER HE REMEMBERS DAVE HILL TALKING IN AN ANGUISHED TONE, HE ALSO NOTED INSTEAD OF LAYING ON THE BUNK HE WAS STANDING ON THE BUNK WALL. DAVE HILL DROVE ON DEPARTURE OF RAYMOND MT. BORDER.  THE ROAD OFFERED GOOD DRIVING CONDITIONS, UNTIL MEETING TRAFFIC.  THE WEATHER WAS WARM, REASONABLY CLEAR TO CULBERTSOR MT. ROAD SPEED WAS 90 KMPH. SOUTH OF CULBERTSON THE WEATHER CHANGED DRASTICALLY.  THE WIND PICKED UP TO APPROXIAMETLY 80 MILES PER HOUR ACCORDING TO THE SHERIFF.  THE WIND WAS GUSTY. THE HIGHWAY #16 MT. BECAME ICY, BUT WAS NOT A PROBLEM.  ONCE PAST SIOUX PASS THE ROAD WAS ICY, THE GUSTY WIND BROUGHT NEAR WHITE VISIBILITY. THE HIGHWAY NARROWS & BECOMES HILLY FROM SIOUX PASS TO SIDNEY MT THUS NO PLACE TO PULL OVER TO PARK WITHOUT CREATING A VERY DISASTROUS SITUATION FOR OTHER ROAD USERS.  THE ONLY WAY TO PROCEED WAS TO OPEN THE DRIVER'S WINDOW TRY TO OBSERVE THE WHITE LINE IN ORDER TO DETERMINE THE VEHICLE'S POSITION ON THE ROAD.  THE WIND GUSTS GOT SO BAD, THE UNIT FELL OFF THE RIGHT SHOULDER OF THE HIGWAY & ROLLED INTO THE DITCH.  THE TIME WOULD BE APPROXIAMETLY DEC.  28/2000.  MIDNIGHT.
